<P>
WHERE ARE THEY NOW?; TOMMY DAVIS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Times Staff Writer David W. Myers catches up with former Dodgers and Angels. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Davis was a high school basketball standout in New York and, according to 
scouts, had a good shot at making the NBA.But Jackie Robinson helped to 
persuade him that baseball was his true calling. 
</P>
<P>
 The outfielder and occasional third-baseman spent the first seven of his 18 
big league seasons with the Dodgers, leading the National League in batting in 
1962 and '63. His .346 average and 153 runs batted in in '62 remain 
single-season records for the Los Angeles franchise. 
</P>
<P>
 Davis, 55, owns a company that specializes in producing promotional caps and 
other items. A resident of San Bernardino County, he also gives private batting 
lessons to children and adults. 
