<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE WEEK AHEAD: CAPE TOWN; MANDELA THE CHOICE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 South Africa's new, multiracial National Assembly, elected last week in the 
country's first all-race polls, will convene Friday in the former whites-only 
Parliament building in Cape Town. 
</P>
<P>
 As its first official act, the 400 members are expected to choose Nelson 
Mandela as president of a government of national unity, based on the 
overwhelming election victory of his African National Congress. The current 
president, Frederik W. de Klerk, is expected to become one of at least two vice 
presidents to Mandela. The number will be determined by the final vote. 
</P>
<P>
 Mandela is to take the oath of office May 10 in Pretoria, setting in motion a 
political transition expected to lead to a new constitution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
