<HEADLINE>
<P>
DISSECTION OF APARTMENTS FOR EVIDENCE BEGINS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ANN W. O'NEILL, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The whine of chain saws in the early-morning fog Monday marked the start of 
the autopsy of Northridge Meadows, where 16 tenants died in the Jan. 17 
earthquake. 
</P>
<P>
 By noon, sections of the roof had been cut away to reveal the insides of the 
building, and a half-dozen lawyers were arguing their cases at a sidewalk news 
conference. 
</P>
<P>
 Former tenants, many from pancaked first-floor units, came to retrieve their 
belongings and were turned away. 
</P>
<P>
 Looking at the place where his mother died -- the exposed mattress, the broken 
walls, the painted letters DB, for dead body -- Bill Runnings felt sick to his 
stomach. Again. 
</P>
<P>
 So began the dismantling of Northridge Meadows, the scene of the largest 
concentration of earthquake fatalities and Exhibit A in seven wrongful death 
and personal injury lawsuits. It could become one of the largest and most 
studied pieces of evidence in Southern California, lawyers said. 
</P>
<P>
 "I just want some answer to why this thing happened so we can move on," said 
Runnings, a 28-year-old roofer from Phoenix. He said he was supposed to visit 
his mother, Karol Runnings, the night she was killed in a quake so powerful it 
drove her bed through the wall. 
</P>
<P>
 It may take months, even years, of testing and study before the experts can 
deliver those answers. Even then, a jury probably will have to decide the 
central issue: whether the collapse of Northridge Meadows was caused by a 
6.8-magnitude earthquake, the quality of the construction or some combination 
of the two. 
</P>
<P>
 Still, Runnings said, respect has drawn him to his mother's shattered 
apartment, where the bed juts out, exposed to the elements. The family 
photographs are in a box in the closet, still underneath somewhere, out of 
reach. But his lawyer, Jeffrey Behar, was there to assure that when the time 
comes, Runnings and his sister, Julie Tindall, 29, will be able to get inside 
Apartment 108. 
</P>
<P>
 Nearly four months after the quake, Tindall said, "it bothers us to know her 
stuff is everywhere and possibly the rats and maggots are getting to it." 
</P>
<P>
 Other former residents were told they must hire attorneys to get inside this 
week, while the experts gather evidence. Later, tenants who hire salvage crews 
can clear out apartments before the city puts the wrecker's ball to Northridge 
Meadows, probably about May 12. 
</P>
<P>
 Engineers, other experts and lawyers -- about 20 in all, according to one 
estimate -- flocked to 9565 Reseda Blvd. for the court-ordered controlled 
demolition. The 164-unit building will be taken apart, piece by piece at times, 
so experts representing all sides can test and study it to determine whether 
construction defects caused or contributed to the fatal collapse. 
</P>
<P>
 They will be looking at the building's connections and supports, as well as 
shear walls and other seismic requirements. 
</P>
<P>
 The engineers started at the top, cutting away several sections of the roof. 
At that pace, it will take at least a week before the critical evidence in the 
40 flattened first-floor apartments is uncovered. 
</P>
<P>
 Attorney Joel Castro, who represents relatives of two women who died, told 
reporters that his engineers had found evidence of another structural defect: 
The third-floor shear walls were not fastened to the roof. Castro maintains 
that the fasteners, which distribute seismic forces that play on the walls, 
were required by building codes. 
</P>
<P>
 But Allen Tharpe, attorney for owner Shasikant Jogani, said there was no 
evidence that the latest alleged defect had caused or contributed to the 
collapse. "After all, the roof didn't collapse," Tharpe said. 
</P>
<P>
 Castro earlier had alleged other defects: That support pipes in the parking 
structures were too thin, that weaker nails were found where stronger nails 
were specified in the building plans, joist hangers were smaller than those 
specified, and floors were supported inadequately with diagonal strips of wood 
rather than plywood. 
</P>
<P>
 Later, Tharpe was encouraged by his own experts' "find": a long board with 
nails jutting out of it. But to Tharpe, it was evidence that the vertical 
forces of the quake had picked the building up and placed it down eight feet to 
the north. The nails, he pointed out, were straight, indicating powerful 
vertical forces were at play, rather than solely lateral forces. 
</P>
<P>
 Castro also alleged for the first time that Northridge Meadows was not built 
to code. As an example, he contended that the tuck-in parking slots were 35 
feet deep -- 10 feet deeper than the 1970 building codes allowed. 
</P>
<P>
 Tharpe and attorneys for builder Brian Heller disputed that contention. 
</P>
<P>
 Jon Mower, the lawyer for Heller, maintained that the complex was built to 
code. Tharpe said Jogani believed Northridge Meadows was built to code when he 
bought it from Heller in 1981, about 10 years after it was built. 
</P>
<P>
 Still, Tharpe said, California law holds Jogani, and other landlords, liable 
for damages when people are killed or injured in their buildings. The legal 
principle is known as "strict liability" and California is one of just a 
handful of states to follow it. 
</P>
<P>
 Nonetheless, Jogani has filed a countersuit against Heller's construction 
company, which in turn is likely to sue its subcontractors. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1991, Jogani was listed as one of Los Angeles' largest residential 
landlords, with holdings worth $385 million. He held liability insurance on 
Northridge Meadows, but no quake insurance. He claims that the earthquake and 
the recession have claimed all his equity. A Shifting Footprint 
</P>
<P>
 A plot plan called a "footprint" will aid in the documentation of structural 
defect evidence being gathered this week in the controlled demolition of he 
Northridge Meadows Apartments. The buildings shifted in several directions 
during the Northridge earthquake-as much as eight feet in some places-according 
to the plan drawn from aerial photographs taken before and after the quake. 
</P>
<P>
 The footprints were drawn up by attorneys representing the building owner. A 
floor-by-floor dismantling of the building is being documented by attorneys, 
engineers, city building and safety personnel survivors and relatives of 
deceased tenants. 
</P>
<P>
 Experts are examining structural elements to determine how the buildings were 
constructed and how the structures performed during the quake. Elements 
analyzed this week will include: Roof and wall diaphragms: Assess the flat 
plywood pieces that form the roof, walls and flooring between floors. 
</P>
<P>
 Shear walls: Determine whether those on the collapsed first floor were where 
they shouldhave been and enough nails and the correct materials were used. 
Hold-downs: Analyze the metal bolts or screws that hold vertical pieces of wood 
to foundation. Source: The law firm of Tharpe & HowellDEMOLITION 
</P>
</TEXT>
